english:
  title: A Memorial of Gratitude for the Imperial Edict
  author: Choe Ham
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your subject humbly reports:

    On the thirteenth day of last September, the Imperial Envoy Seokyeong Military Commissioner and Concurrent Court Counselor Ko Baek-suk, along with Deputy Envoy Hong Nok-kyeong and Court Ritual Inspector O Ji-chung, arrived bearing the imperial edict and separate documents. His Majesty graciously bestowed upon your subject robes, silk bolts, and silver vessels. On the twenty-fourth day, Commissioner Ko and his delegation privately conveyed the imperial will: the city of Pojou shall be restored to Goryeo's domain and shall not be reclaimed. Such abundant benevolence, such weighty proclamations—I bow in gratitude while trembling with awe and reverence.

    I humbly contemplate:

    The Emperor embodies virtues beyond naming and manifests a will of boundless achievement. Like thunder that stirs and wind that sweeps across all lands, he wields power unmatched. Heaven's mandate aligns with human hearts; thus his works stand extraordinary and eternal.

    Our realm, remote and isolated in distant reaches, has harbored admiration for the great court from ancient times. The Middle Kingdom's righteous campaigns, launched repeatedly, were undertaken because our small nation faced such tribulations that tribute payments were delayed. Though our ceremonies fell short, our hearts held no other intention. Recently, upon receiving imperial recognition of our humble submission, we scarcely dared hope that envoys would follow in succession, bringing such imperial favor. This honor stirs our loyalty to serve the great, bestowing grace as abundant as rain from heaven.

    Moreover, through secret edict and intimate counsel, His Majesty has shown mercy: Pojou shall not be reclaimed; Pyongyang shall know peace. The territories bounded by the Yalu have been ours since ancient times. Yet the Khitan seized them in recent generations; though we maintained cordial relations, they long refused restoration. When that kingdom fell and its garrison scattered, my father, the late prince, declared: "This is rightfully our land. We have sought its return for ages. Now Heaven grants it—we need only take what is ours." Furthermore, the late emperor's envoy Sha-ha transmitted the imperial decree: "Pojou is naturally Goryeo territory; Goryeo should rightfully possess it." Thus we dispatched officials and restored the populace.

    Years passed, and the mandate came to me. Now, by the guidance of the great court, our small realm's borders are confirmed. Regarding those who crossed into both regions—whether they remain or have perished after so many years in this different land—Your Majesty has magnanimously instructed us to manage this matter as circumstances permit. Such extraordinary grace exceeds all precedent.

    With such tender compassion shown to us, how can we ever repay such kindness? Your subject vows solemnly to honor the imperial teachings, to faithfully render tribute without fail through endless years, and to uphold righteous loyalty to the throne, a legacy for generations to come.
  footnotes:
    - 'Pojou (保州): A strategic city on the Korean peninsula, historically contested and sought by Goryeo after the fall of the Khitan-led Liao dynasty.'
    - 'Yalu (鴨綠): The major river serving as a natural boundary between Korea and China, symbolizing the ancient borders of Korean territory.'
    - The 'two regions' (兩界) likely refers to border areas where populations had migrated or been displaced due to warfare and political changes.
